WEBVTT

00:00:00.320 --> 00:00:02.080
Without further ado, let's get your ducks in a row,

00:00:02.080 --> 00:00:04.500
Faster Shiny Apps with DuckDB.

00:00:05.520 --> 00:00:08.560
So if you get nothing else out of this talk,

00:00:09.560 --> 00:00:12.360
I hope you realize that slow, shiny apps

00:00:12.360 --> 00:00:14.360
are a lifestyle problem,

00:00:14.360 --> 00:00:16.280
and they're cumbersome, frustrating,

00:00:16.280 --> 00:00:18.440
and they make people's day worse,

00:00:18.440 --> 00:00:20.719
but you don't have to deal with it.

00:00:20.719 --> 00:00:23.600
We solved this problem by caching results in DuckDB,

00:00:23.600 --> 00:00:25.480
and using that to feed our shiny app.

00:00:25.480 --> 00:00:27.160
And we got faster app performance

00:00:27.160 --> 00:00:29.000
for no infrastructure cost on our end,

00:00:29.040 --> 00:00:30.440
and very minimal effort.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:34.240
All right, so a little bit about who I am.

00:00:34.240 --> 00:00:37.639
I work for the New York State Office of General Services.

00:00:37.639 --> 00:00:39.520
I've been with New York State for over 20 years,

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:41.000
but these opinions are my own,

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:43.119
and don't reflect New York State policy.

00:00:44.040 --> 00:00:45.619
I just moved to Office of General Services

00:00:45.619 --> 00:00:47.160
earlier this year, but before that,

00:00:47.160 --> 00:00:50.180
I was with the Department of Environmental Conservation

00:00:50.180 --> 00:00:53.380
for most of my time as a marine biologist.

00:00:53.380 --> 00:00:56.200
And you probably have ideas about what marine biologists do.

00:00:56.200 --> 00:00:57.959
Everyone gets excited when I say that.

00:00:57.959 --> 00:01:00.160
I think you swim with dolphins, save whales,

00:01:01.320 --> 00:01:02.759
or you're out in the field,

00:01:02.759 --> 00:01:06.400
maybe on a boat surveying surf clams in the Atlantic.

00:01:06.400 --> 00:01:09.000
And they imagine it's a lot of field-based work,

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:10.519
but there is a lot of quantitative work

00:01:10.519 --> 00:01:12.900
that's happening in certain sub-disciplines,

00:01:12.900 --> 00:01:15.379
such as fisheries management and fishery science,

00:01:15.379 --> 00:01:17.239
which is where I eventually ended up.

00:01:18.639 --> 00:01:19.800
I can't believe they found a picture

00:01:19.800 --> 00:01:21.239
of me smiling on that boat.

00:01:21.239 --> 00:01:23.320
It was probably when we got back to the dock.

00:01:23.320 --> 00:01:26.320
I get very seasick, so I'm moving over

00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:28.559
into more of a data science role

00:01:28.559 --> 00:01:30.059
worked out really well for me.

00:01:31.919 --> 00:01:34.839
And while I was at DEC, I led a few small data teams.

00:01:34.839 --> 00:01:37.160
And when I'm saying small, less than 10 people,

00:01:37.160 --> 00:01:39.320
all of whom were marine biologists.

00:01:39.320 --> 00:01:43.879
There is no software development person,

00:01:43.879 --> 00:01:44.919
no database admin.

00:01:44.919 --> 00:01:48.559
We were kind of an insular group

00:01:49.480 --> 00:01:51.320
working on fishery science questions

00:01:51.320 --> 00:01:53.519
and managing that data for New York.

00:01:53.519 --> 00:01:55.339
And we always start out with Excel and Access,

00:01:55.339 --> 00:01:57.220
because that's what you have when you start,

00:01:57.220 --> 00:01:59.180
and we always outgrew it.

00:01:59.180 --> 00:02:02.699
It couldn't do the kind of analysis and reports

00:02:02.699 --> 00:02:04.379
in a repeatable way that we were looking.

00:02:04.379 --> 00:02:07.180
So we had to figure out something else.

00:02:08.100 --> 00:02:09.740
Also, since we're such a small team,

00:02:09.740 --> 00:02:12.880
there's no off-the-shelf software for fisheries management.

00:02:12.880 --> 00:02:14.139
Every state does it a little different,

00:02:14.139 --> 00:02:16.179
so there's no consistency.

00:02:16.179 --> 00:02:18.199
And that's where R and Shiny came in.

00:02:18.199 --> 00:02:20.300
Those tools were available to us,

00:02:20.300 --> 00:02:23.000
and the ability to create our own custom tools

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:24.500
was a real game-changer.

00:02:26.259 --> 00:02:29.139
But, and there's always a but,

00:02:29.139 --> 00:02:31.720
as it became more widely used,

00:02:32.899 --> 00:02:35.979
it eventually started getting sluggish and frustrating,

00:02:35.979 --> 00:02:38.720
and it wasn't the big success that it was in the beginning.

00:02:38.720 --> 00:02:40.339
People were getting annoyed all the time.

00:02:40.339 --> 00:02:43.100
So how do we address that?

00:02:44.619 --> 00:02:46.539
So to give you an idea about what our system looked like

00:02:46.539 --> 00:02:49.339
at the beginning, it started out with a SQL server.

00:02:49.339 --> 00:02:50.940
We had to get all our data in one place.

00:02:50.940 --> 00:02:53.820
We were previously using distributed access databases,

00:02:53.820 --> 00:02:55.619
which were terrible because we needed

00:02:56.740 --> 00:02:58.580
one for a year's worth of data.

00:02:58.580 --> 00:03:00.460
Nothing fit.

00:03:00.460 --> 00:03:02.500
Once we got the data in the server,

00:03:02.500 --> 00:03:04.820
the next part was to create an internal package

00:03:04.820 --> 00:03:05.820
for us to use.

00:03:05.820 --> 00:03:07.860
We had to make sure everyone was counting fish

00:03:07.860 --> 00:03:08.820
the exact same way.

00:03:10.740 --> 00:03:13.059
And once that was done,

00:03:13.059 --> 00:03:14.979
it made sense to make a Shiny front-end

00:03:14.979 --> 00:03:17.679
so that we didn't have to look at the code all the time.

00:03:17.679 --> 00:03:19.479
We could view it in a browser.

00:03:21.259 --> 00:03:23.259
And that was wonderful for a while.

00:03:23.820 --> 00:03:28.820
Until, we did have some constraints on us.

00:03:32.460 --> 00:03:34.979
One, all of our team was running a Shiny app locally.

00:03:34.979 --> 00:03:36.740
We did not have access to a Shiny server,

00:03:36.740 --> 00:03:39.399
so everyone had to clone the repo,

00:03:39.399 --> 00:03:41.500
make sure it ran on their machine.

00:03:41.500 --> 00:03:43.699
And that was okay.

00:03:43.699 --> 00:03:45.259
People were using it every day.

00:03:47.059 --> 00:03:49.220
Doing the queries, running the reports,

00:03:49.220 --> 00:03:51.979
and they would get ideas about how it could be better.

00:03:52.740 --> 00:03:55.419
And they'd be really good ideas.

00:03:55.419 --> 00:03:58.179
And since we were in control of app development,

00:03:58.179 --> 00:04:01.419
we got to decide what we wanted to add and what we didn't.

00:04:01.419 --> 00:04:02.539
And so the cycle continued.

00:04:02.539 --> 00:04:05.039
In every iteration, the app got better and better.

00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:11.580
But eventually, things started to catch up to us.

00:04:11.580 --> 00:04:14.000
Imagine, if you've ever waited tables,

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:15.259
you're probably familiar with this problem,

00:04:15.259 --> 00:04:17.779
or maybe it's a problem at your dinner table

00:04:17.779 --> 00:04:19.100
with your own family.

00:04:19.100 --> 00:04:20.799
But back in college, I waited tables,

00:04:20.799 --> 00:04:22.640
and you'd go to your four-top,

00:04:22.640 --> 00:04:23.480
and someone would say,

00:04:23.480 --> 00:04:25.100
hey, can I have a glass of water?

00:04:25.100 --> 00:04:26.000
You'd say, sure, no problem.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:27.920
You'd go get the glass of water, and you'd bring it back.

00:04:27.920 --> 00:04:30.679
And then the second person would ask for a glass of water.

00:04:30.679 --> 00:04:32.160
You'd go, you'd get the glass of water,

00:04:32.160 --> 00:04:33.760
and you'd bring it back.

00:04:33.760 --> 00:04:36.399
And now the third person also wants a glass of water.

00:04:36.399 --> 00:04:37.920
And at this point, you're just like, you know, come on.

00:04:37.920 --> 00:04:40.679
Couldn't we have done this all in one shot?

00:04:40.679 --> 00:04:42.679
So you wise up, and you also ask the fourth person

00:04:42.679 --> 00:04:45.380
at the same time if they want a glass of water, too.

00:04:45.380 --> 00:04:46.799
And this was a pretty good analogy

00:04:46.799 --> 00:04:48.239
on how our app was running.

00:04:48.320 --> 00:04:51.279
It wasn't well thought out,

00:04:51.279 --> 00:04:53.079
because it was built to do a very small thing to start,

00:04:53.079 --> 00:04:54.980
and we kept adding all these features.

00:04:56.519 --> 00:05:00.239
So in terms of the app, as with all shiny apps,

00:05:00.239 --> 00:05:02.399
you know, we had an interface that took inputs

00:05:02.399 --> 00:05:04.040
and then returned results.

00:05:04.040 --> 00:05:05.320
And every time you changed an input,

00:05:05.320 --> 00:05:07.279
that was a new query to the SQL server.

00:05:08.640 --> 00:05:11.600
And we found out each query took like eight seconds.

00:05:11.600 --> 00:05:13.760
And that's an eternity.

00:05:13.760 --> 00:05:15.119
I thought about just sitting in silence

00:05:15.119 --> 00:05:15.959
for eight seconds up here,

00:05:15.959 --> 00:05:18.799
but I thought it would be too uncomfortable for all of us.

00:05:21.279 --> 00:05:23.459
So where was this bottleneck happening?

00:05:24.679 --> 00:05:26.980
It was with all these calls to the SQL server.

00:05:28.579 --> 00:05:30.480
Every time we had a new question,

00:05:30.480 --> 00:05:32.480
we'd go back to the source to get the answer,

00:05:32.480 --> 00:05:34.920
recalculate everything, and display results.

00:05:34.920 --> 00:05:38.119
So too many queries, run too often,

00:05:38.119 --> 00:05:40.160
and most of them were really unnecessary.

00:05:41.519 --> 00:05:43.519
And this is where DuckDB came in.

00:05:44.519 --> 00:05:47.720
We decided we should try pre-processing all this data

00:05:48.880 --> 00:05:50.720
and doing everything in one fell swoop at the beginning

00:05:50.720 --> 00:05:52.040
when people opened the app.

00:05:52.040 --> 00:05:54.119
So DuckDB gave us an easy way to create

00:05:54.119 --> 00:05:58.320
a single file of that data, again, with no cost to us,

00:05:58.320 --> 00:06:00.940
no additional infrastructure needs.

00:06:00.940 --> 00:06:02.279
It worked out of the box

00:06:02.279 --> 00:06:04.079
with everything we were already using.

00:06:04.079 --> 00:06:05.279
And since it was approved by IT,

00:06:05.279 --> 00:06:07.880
we could implement it ourselves and didn't have to wait.

00:06:07.880 --> 00:06:09.779
And if that wasn't enough,

00:06:09.779 --> 00:06:14.100
and that was enough for us to decide to give this a try,

00:06:14.100 --> 00:06:16.100
it also added spatial capabilities to our data

00:06:16.100 --> 00:06:18.239
that weren't available in the SQL server we were using.

00:06:18.239 --> 00:06:21.660
So in the future, we had the option to increase

00:06:22.940 --> 00:06:26.420
some of our QA, QC, and mapping capabilities that way.

00:06:26.420 --> 00:06:30.299
So where does this fit in with the workflow we had?

00:06:32.619 --> 00:06:35.700
Our SQL server is still the database of record.

00:06:35.700 --> 00:06:37.420
That is where all the data entry goes.

00:06:37.420 --> 00:06:38.980
That's where all the corrections go.

00:06:38.980 --> 00:06:43.339
When we find mistakes, but it's just really slow.

00:06:43.339 --> 00:06:47.500
So we wanted our app to call that server only once

00:06:47.500 --> 00:06:51.059
on opening, and then write a file locally

00:06:51.059 --> 00:06:52.839
that holds all of that data.

00:06:55.100 --> 00:06:58.899
So now, what is in the DuckDB file?

00:06:58.899 --> 00:07:01.260
It's a series of tables that has the raw data,

00:07:01.260 --> 00:07:04.459
the row-level data that the app needs to be able to display.

00:07:04.459 --> 00:07:07.059
It also has the results of all our calculations

00:07:07.059 --> 00:07:09.140
and aggregations stored as separate tables.

00:07:09.140 --> 00:07:11.579
So everything is happening immediately

00:07:11.579 --> 00:07:15.440
when the app is opened, and the app no longer

00:07:15.440 --> 00:07:19.500
has to do calculations or queries on the fly.

00:07:19.500 --> 00:07:22.619
So we have essentially asked for all four glasses of water

00:07:22.619 --> 00:07:24.619
at the beginning when we opened the app.

00:07:26.100 --> 00:07:27.579
And I'm just gonna show you a little bit

00:07:27.579 --> 00:07:30.140
of where we made the changes into the code

00:07:30.140 --> 00:07:31.579
to make this happen.

00:07:31.700 --> 00:07:36.700
So we're using pretty standard, shiny dashboard stuff,

00:07:37.700 --> 00:07:41.220
where we call our libraries at the beginning,

00:07:41.220 --> 00:07:43.420
and then we run a bunch of source files at the top.

00:07:43.420 --> 00:07:46.179
I'm gonna talk about the specifics on the next slide,

00:07:46.179 --> 00:07:49.059
because that's where all the changes are happening.

00:07:49.059 --> 00:07:53.899
But the header, the body, and the sidebar remain untouched,

00:07:53.899 --> 00:07:56.399
as do the UI and server functions.

00:07:57.619 --> 00:08:00.420
So we didn't have to change anything on that app

00:08:00.420 --> 00:08:01.940
that people are opening and running.

00:08:01.940 --> 00:08:04.019
What we did have to change was some of the files

00:08:04.019 --> 00:08:07.260
and modules we were calling at the beginning of the app.

00:08:07.260 --> 00:08:09.839
So we have our functions for the app,

00:08:09.839 --> 00:08:13.779
and we have all our modules, but we wanted to add

00:08:13.779 --> 00:08:15.839
a script that did that data pull

00:08:15.839 --> 00:08:19.220
and all those calculations for us, and stored it locally.

00:08:19.220 --> 00:08:21.899
So we created a very creatively named app

00:08:21.899 --> 00:08:23.959
called the CreateDuckDB database.

00:08:25.260 --> 00:08:28.700
And in that script, we're using DuckDB and DBI,

00:08:28.700 --> 00:08:30.980
although I'm gonna have to look into Duckplier later

00:08:30.980 --> 00:08:32.539
to see if that would be better.

00:08:33.900 --> 00:08:36.419
And we're making the database.

00:08:36.419 --> 00:08:37.960
If the database already exists,

00:08:37.960 --> 00:08:42.140
it just references it with that one line.

00:08:42.140 --> 00:08:46.380
And now here's where we do our time-expensive SQL queries

00:08:46.380 --> 00:08:48.799
and all of the calculations.

00:08:48.799 --> 00:08:49.979
We save them as a data frame,

00:08:49.979 --> 00:08:53.760
and then write them to tables in the database.

00:08:53.760 --> 00:08:54.599
And that's it.

00:08:56.500 --> 00:08:57.700
Additionally, we just had to make sure

00:08:57.700 --> 00:08:59.140
all of our modules were referencing,

00:08:59.140 --> 00:09:00.419
pointing to the right database.

00:09:00.419 --> 00:09:01.820
And since that was defined at the top

00:09:01.820 --> 00:09:04.739
of each of those scripts, it was very easy.

00:09:04.739 --> 00:09:06.559
This was probably an afternoon of work

00:09:06.559 --> 00:09:11.200
to get a testable version ready for everybody else.

00:09:12.539 --> 00:09:15.619
And the results were great.

00:09:15.619 --> 00:09:19.739
We went from an eight-second query many, many times

00:09:19.739 --> 00:09:22.219
throughout the app, because people could be using this

00:09:22.219 --> 00:09:24.859
for hours, they usually had it open all day,

00:09:24.859 --> 00:09:26.659
to pretty much instantaneous changes

00:09:26.659 --> 00:09:28.659
when we changed the input.

00:09:28.659 --> 00:09:31.219
The boot-up time for the app was like two seconds longer,

00:09:31.219 --> 00:09:33.539
so even if they only opened it to a run-run query,

00:09:33.539 --> 00:09:36.020
we were still ahead by six seconds.

00:09:36.020 --> 00:09:38.020
So it made the app feel much better to use.

00:09:38.020 --> 00:09:40.020
It was less frustrating.

00:09:40.020 --> 00:09:41.619
We were able to do it ourselves.

00:09:41.619 --> 00:09:46.619
And again, I can't emphasize the low-cost, no-cost enough,

00:09:47.619 --> 00:09:49.460
because we don't really have a budget

00:09:49.460 --> 00:09:51.299
to make these changes on the fly.

00:09:51.299 --> 00:09:52.559
I'm sure if any of you are working

00:09:52.559 --> 00:09:53.719
in the public sector in government,

00:09:53.719 --> 00:09:55.559
you understand how long it takes

00:09:55.559 --> 00:09:58.200
to get those things established.

00:09:58.200 --> 00:10:00.799
But there are some big caveats I want to talk about.

00:10:01.919 --> 00:10:05.280
And it has to do with storing the data locally on the PCs.

00:10:05.280 --> 00:10:06.979
Because remember, everyone's making a copy

00:10:06.979 --> 00:10:10.039
and putting it on their machine for that shiny app to run.

00:10:10.039 --> 00:10:12.440
So depending on when they open up their app in the morning,

00:10:12.440 --> 00:10:14.440
there is a chance they could have different data sets

00:10:14.440 --> 00:10:16.760
between two people in the office.

00:10:16.760 --> 00:10:18.760
Most of the time, that's not a problem,

00:10:18.760 --> 00:10:21.039
but there could be situations where

00:10:21.039 --> 00:10:23.599
they're getting different results for the same task,

00:10:24.479 --> 00:10:26.280
and the most likely reason is that

00:10:27.159 --> 00:10:28.760
something happened, there was a big data upload

00:10:28.760 --> 00:10:31.239
between the times they started the app.

00:10:32.359 --> 00:10:37.359
Because we are uploading hundreds of records every day,

00:10:38.880 --> 00:10:40.119
so in the grand scheme of things,

00:10:40.119 --> 00:10:40.979
that's not really a difference

00:10:40.979 --> 00:10:42.640
when you're looking at hundreds of thousands of records,

00:10:42.640 --> 00:10:45.719
but just by bad luck, it could make a difference

00:10:45.719 --> 00:10:48.159
if you're helping a specific customer.

00:10:48.159 --> 00:10:49.559
And the other issue, again,

00:10:49.559 --> 00:10:51.119
with that local storage of the file,

00:10:51.119 --> 00:10:53.280
is that you need to be conscious

00:10:53.280 --> 00:10:56.760
that it meets the permissions your user is allowed to have.

00:10:57.640 --> 00:10:59.440
In our situation, everybody could look at

00:10:59.440 --> 00:11:03.080
row-level and trip-level data as part of their job,

00:11:03.080 --> 00:11:06.559
but if your users were only supposed to look at

00:11:06.559 --> 00:11:08.440
calculations or aggregations of the data,

00:11:08.440 --> 00:11:10.479
you don't want to store the row-level data

00:11:10.479 --> 00:11:11.880
in the DuckDB database,

00:11:11.880 --> 00:11:13.599
because then they could look at it

00:11:14.479 --> 00:11:16.080
even if they're not supposed to.

00:11:17.080 --> 00:11:21.080
And I feel like I ran through that so fast.

00:11:21.080 --> 00:11:25.799
But yeah, so my name is Melissa Albino-Hageman.

00:11:25.799 --> 00:11:27.760
I'm with the Office of General Services.

00:11:27.760 --> 00:11:29.760
You can check out our public-facing projects

00:11:29.760 --> 00:11:31.960
at ogs.ny.gov.

00:11:31.960 --> 00:11:34.000
You can find me on LinkedIn and GitHub

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:35.940
at melissahageman.com.

00:11:35.940 --> 00:11:39.200
I will have notes from today up later this evening,

00:11:39.200 --> 00:11:40.719
and I'm trying to be more active on Blue Sky

00:11:40.719 --> 00:11:42.599
around our stuff, so you can find me there

00:11:42.599 --> 00:11:45.140
at mellikesmaps, and thank you very much.

00:11:46.080 --> 00:11:46.919
Thank you.

00:11:46.919 --> 00:11:47.739
Thank you.

00:11:47.739 --> 00:11:48.580
Thank you.

00:11:48.580 --> 00:11:49.419
Thank you.

00:11:49.419 --> 00:11:50.239
Thank you.

00:11:50.239 --> 00:11:51.080
Thank you.

00:11:51.080 --> 00:11:51.919
Thank you.

00:11:51.919 --> 00:11:52.739
Thank you.

00:11:52.739 --> 00:11:54.200
Thank you, Melissa.

00:11:54.200 --> 00:11:57.039
We've got some questions, so the first one.

00:11:57.039 --> 00:11:59.320
How do you decide what data to cache?

00:11:59.320 --> 00:12:00.679
Are you caching everything?

00:12:03.280 --> 00:12:05.640
It was kind of based on what people were using.

00:12:05.640 --> 00:12:08.119
We started with the stuff that was most important

00:12:08.119 --> 00:12:10.000
on the daily basis, and

00:12:12.359 --> 00:12:13.840
we only have eight users, so it's really easy

00:12:13.840 --> 00:12:15.840
to get very specific data.

00:12:16.599 --> 00:12:18.239
If they say, hey, five of us can't do this,

00:12:18.239 --> 00:12:20.520
then it's easy to choose to fix that problem.

00:12:26.080 --> 00:12:27.799
What advice do you have for shiny apps

00:12:27.799 --> 00:12:30.200
that process data based on user input,

00:12:30.200 --> 00:12:31.940
not processed all at the start?

00:12:32.880 --> 00:12:34.479
I'm sorry, repeat that?

00:12:34.479 --> 00:12:36.479
What advice do you have for shiny apps

00:12:36.479 --> 00:12:39.239
that process data based on user input,

00:12:39.239 --> 00:12:40.960
not processed all at the start?

00:12:41.960 --> 00:12:46.159
Well, you could guess what they want

00:12:46.159 --> 00:12:48.799
and pre-process some things ahead of time.

00:12:48.799 --> 00:12:49.840
In this case,

00:12:52.919 --> 00:12:54.799
the output changed based on the user input,

00:12:54.799 --> 00:12:56.599
but everything was calculated beforehand,

00:12:56.599 --> 00:12:58.799
so they were choosing options

00:12:58.799 --> 00:13:00.440
that had already been calculated.

00:13:06.640 --> 00:13:08.440
Why keep the SQL server

00:13:08.440 --> 00:13:10.440
rather than move everything to DuckDB?

00:13:11.440 --> 00:13:12.640
That's a good question.

00:13:14.080 --> 00:13:16.119
DuckDB isn't designed to enter transactions,

00:13:16.119 --> 00:13:18.799
so we have another application for data entry.

00:13:18.799 --> 00:13:22.559
We are still entering a lot of paper in this program,

00:13:22.559 --> 00:13:26.400
so that's not what DuckDB is designed for,

00:13:26.400 --> 00:13:27.239
is my understanding.

00:13:27.239 --> 00:13:29.960
It's more of a searching retrieval database.

00:13:30.960 --> 00:13:32.280
The SQL server's also backed up

00:13:32.280 --> 00:13:34.119
if that's supported by IT,

00:13:34.119 --> 00:13:36.400
and I do not want to mess around

00:13:36.400 --> 00:13:39.960
with losing 20 years of Fisheries data, so.

00:13:41.960 --> 00:13:46.719
Is there an official CountFish package,

00:13:46.719 --> 00:13:47.880
asking for a friend?

00:13:47.880 --> 00:13:49.559
Oh no, I made that up.

00:13:49.559 --> 00:13:51.640
We do have an official package,

00:13:51.640 --> 00:13:54.159
but it is not publicly available,

00:13:54.159 --> 00:13:56.599
and it would only really work for New York anyway.

00:13:56.599 --> 00:13:58.280
I think even if there's not an official package,

00:13:58.280 --> 00:14:00.239
you can have the HEC sticker available.

00:14:00.239 --> 00:14:02.359
People would be into that.

00:14:02.359 --> 00:14:03.520
And I have a question.

00:14:03.520 --> 00:14:05.599
You mentioned you only have eight users.

00:14:05.599 --> 00:14:06.440
Yes.

00:14:06.440 --> 00:14:07.880
What do you think the considerations would be

00:14:07.880 --> 00:14:09.080
if you wanted to scale that up

00:14:09.080 --> 00:14:11.760
to a larger number of users?

00:14:11.760 --> 00:14:14.320
Like I said, the permissions make a big difference,

00:14:14.320 --> 00:14:15.440
and I'd have to think carefully

00:14:15.440 --> 00:14:17.280
about how we store the data.

00:14:17.280 --> 00:14:20.039
If we want people who don't have access

00:14:20.039 --> 00:14:23.599
to everything to even use that database,

00:14:23.599 --> 00:14:25.359
we might have to do something else.

00:14:28.159 --> 00:14:31.520
For folks about to embark on the same journey you did,

00:14:31.520 --> 00:14:33.479
any hard-earned lessons you wish

00:14:33.479 --> 00:14:35.239
you knew about before you started?

00:14:36.080 --> 00:14:38.200
That your first versions are gonna be horrible,

00:14:38.200 --> 00:14:39.359
and that's okay.

00:14:41.880 --> 00:14:43.119
All right, thank you very much,

00:14:43.119 --> 00:14:45.080
and I hope to see you all in the keynote shortly.

00:14:45.080 --> 00:14:46.320
Let's thank our speakers again.

00:14:46.320 --> 00:14:47.200
Thank you.

